<section xml:id="sec-explore-sci-not" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Explore</title>

    <!-- Start of Worksheet -->
    <worksheet xml:id="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation">
        <title>Explore: Scientific Notation</title>

        <!-- Objectives -->
        <objectives>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    Reinforce your ability to convert between standard and scientific notation and interpret the meaning of powers of ten in real-world and scientific contexts.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </objectives>
        <!-- Introduction -->
        <introduction>
            <p>
                This worksheet is designed to help you explore the concept of scientific notation in physics.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <!-- Page 01 -->
        <page>
            <pagebreak/> <!-- Worksheet Exercise 01 --> <!-- Influenza virus size -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in" xml:id="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation-01">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Influenza">influenza virus</url> can have a diameter of about <m>0.000000099</m> meters.
                        Convert <m>0.000000099</m> to scientific notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        The decimal point would need to move to the right by <m>8</m> places.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>9.9 \times 10^{-8}</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        To write <m>0.000000099</m> in scientific notation, move the decimal point <em>eight places to the right</em> to place it after the first nonzero digit.
                        This gives <m>9.9</m>.
                        Since the decimal moved right by eight places, the exponent on <m>10</m> is <m>-8</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>0.000000099 = 9.9 \times 10^{-8}</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 02 --> <!-- Human hair diameter -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in" xml:id="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation-02">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A strand of human hair is about <m>0.00007</m> meters in diameter.
                        Convert <m>0.00007</m> to scientific notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        The decimal point would need to move to the right by <m>5</m> places.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>7.0 \times 10^{-5}</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        To write <m>0.00007</m> in scientific notation, move the decimal point <em>five places to the right</em> to place it after the first nonzero digit.
                        This gives <m>7.0</m>.
                        Since the decimal moved right by five places, the exponent on <m>10</m> is <m>-5</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>0.00007 = 7.0 \times 10^{-5}</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 03 --> <!-- Grain of sand diameter -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in" xml:id="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation-03">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A grain of sand can be about <m>0.0012</m> meters in diameter.
                        Convert <m>0.0012</m> to scientific notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        The decimal point would need to move to the right by <m>3</m> places.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>1.2 \times 10^{-3}</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        To write <m>0.0012</m> in scientific notation, move the decimal point <em>three places to the right</em> to place it after the first nonzero digit.
                        This gives <m>1.2</m>.
                        Since the decimal moved right by three places, the exponent on <m>10</m> is <m>-3</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>0.0012 = 1.2 \times 10^{-3}</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 04 --> <!-- Average human height -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in" xml:id="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation-04">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        An average adult human might be about <m>1.75</m> meters tall.
                        Convert <m>1.75</m> to scientific notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        The decimal point would need to move to the left by <m>0</m> places.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>1.75 \times 10^{0}</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        To write <m>1.75</m> in scientific notation, the decimal is already after the first nonzero digit, so we don't need to move it.
                        That means the exponent on <m>10</m> is <m>0</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>1.75 = 1.75 \times 10^{0}</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 05 --> <!-- Empire State Building height -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in" xml:id="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation-05">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The Empire State Building in New York City is about <m>3.81 \times 10^{2}</m> meters tall.
                        Convert <m>3.81 \times 10^{2}</m> to standard notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        A positive exponent means move the decimal to the right.
                        Move it <m>2</m> places to the right.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>381</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>3.81 \times 10^{2}</m> means move the decimal point <m>2</m> places to the right: <m>3.81 \rightarrow 38.1 \rightarrow 381.</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>3.81 \times 10^{2} = 381</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 06 --> <!-- Mount Everest height -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in" xml:id="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation-06">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Mount Everest is approximately <m>8.85 \times 10^{3}</m> meters tall.
                        Convert <m>8.85 \times 10^{3}</m> to standard notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        Move the decimal point <m>3</m> places to the right.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>8850</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>8.85 \times 10^{3}</m> means move the decimal <m>3</m> places to the right: <m>8.85 \rightarrow 88.5 \rightarrow 885 \rightarrow 8850</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>8.85 \times 10^{3} = 8850</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 07 --> <!-- Earth's diameter -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in" xml:id="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation-07">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The Earth's diameter is about <m>1.27 \times 10^{7}</m> meters.
                        Convert <m>1.27 \times 10^{7}</m> to standard notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        Move the decimal <m>7</m> places to the right.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>12,700,000</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>1.27 \times 10^{7}</m> means move the decimal <m>7</m> places to the right: <m>1.27 \rightarrow 12.7 \rightarrow 127 \rightarrow … \rightarrow 12700000</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>1.27 \times 10^{7} = 12,700,000</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 08 --> <!-- Distance from Earth to Sun -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in" xml:id="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation-08">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The average distance from Earth to the Sun is about <m>1.496 \times 10^{11}</m> meters.
                        Convert <m>1.496 \times 10^{11}</m> to standard notation.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        Move the decimal <m>11</m> places to the right.
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>149,600,000,000</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>1.496 \times 10^{11}</m> means move the decimal <m>11</m> places to the right: <m>1.496 \rightarrow 14.96 \rightarrow 149.6 \rightarrow … \rightarrow 149600000000</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, <m>1.496 \times 10^{11} = 149600000000</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 09 --> <!-- Human height vs grain of sand -->
            <exercise workspace="0.2in" xml:id="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation-09">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        About how many orders of magnitude larger is a human compared to a grain of sand? <em>Use questions <xref ref="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation-03"/> and <xref ref="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation-04"/> to help.</em>
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        Compare the exponents: <m>10^{0}</m> vs.
                        <m>10^{-3}</m>.
                        How many powers of ten apart are they?
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>3</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The exponent for the human's height is <m>0</m>, and for the grain of sand it is <m>-3</m>.
                        The difference is <m>0 - (-3) = 3</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, a human is approximately <em>3 orders of magnitude</em> larger than a grain of sand.
                        This means the human is about <m>10^3 = 1000</m> times taller than the grain of sand.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        In other words, if you stacked <m>1000</m> grains of sand end to end, they would reach about the height of one person!
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
            <!-- Worksheet Exercise 10 --> <!-- Human height vs influenza virus -->
            <exercise xml:id="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation-10">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        About how many orders of magnitude larger is a human compared to an influenza virus? <em>Use questions <xref ref="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation-01"/> and <xref ref="worksheet-explore-scientific-notation-04"/> to help.</em>
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <hint>
                    <p>
                        Compare the exponents: <m>10^{0}</m> vs.
                        <m>10^{-8}</m>.
                        How many powers of ten apart are they?
                    </p>
                </hint>

                <answer>
                    <p>
                        <m>8</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The exponent for the human's height is <m>0</m>, and for the virus it is <m>-8</m>.
                        The difference is <m>0 - (-8) = 8</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, a human is approximately <em>eight orders of magnitude</em> larger than the influenza virus.
                        This means the human is about <m>10^8 = 100000000</m> times taller than the virus.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        In other words, if you stacked <m>100000000</m> viruses end to end, they would reach about the height of one person!
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
        </page>
    </worksheet>
